 {"id":"flywheel_connectors-qnchs.16","title":"[CUAL-W] CLI Dispatch Wiring and Command-Family Activation","description":"# Track W: CLI Dispatch Wiring and Command-Family Activation

## Why This Track Exists
Two different kinds of CLI work belong here, and both are easy to under-specify if they stay scattered across feature beads:
1. substantial CUAL modules already exist with real logic and tests but still need explicit CLI dispatch glue
2. newer ergonomic tracks introduce major command families such as `fwc access`, `fwc setup`, and `fwc mesh`, and those families need an explicit home for clap wiring, routing, output shaping, preview-vs-execute behavior, and exit-code consistency

## Current State
Existing modules with implemented logic that still need dedicated or remaining dispatch glue:
- serve_mcp.rs (2,159 lines, 116 tests) — MCP server, needs `fwc serve-mcp` command wiring
- credential_store.rs (1,265 lines, 93 tests) — needs `fwc auth` command wiring
- audit.rs (2,112 lines, 93 tests) — needs audit query integration
- event_stream.rs (1,000 lines, 76 tests) — needs `fwc events` command wiring
- throttle.rs (1,398 lines, 68 tests) — needs execution-path middleware injection

Track G already owns map/batch execution and progress surfaces, so this track should not duplicate batch wiring unless a concrete new dispatch gap is discovered.

CLI commands using `planned()` stubs or otherwise incomplete routing still include:
- invoke, simulate, status, enable, disable, start, stop, restart, install, update, pin, unpin, config, logs, events

In addition, new command families introduced by later CUAL tracks must not be treated as implicitly wired just because their behavior is designed. They need explicit activation beads here.

## What This Track Delivers
- explicit clap/dispatch/output wiring beads for remaining dead-code or partially routed modules
- command-family activation beads for `fwc access`, `fwc setup`, and `fwc mesh`
- clear ownership for read-only versus side-effecting subcommands, preview-versus-execute semantics, session-context interaction, TOON/JSON output parity, and stable `FCP_ERR_*` envelopes at the CLI boundary
- a rule that no feature track is considered user-ready while its command surface is still partially stubbed, ambiguously routed, or missing dispatch tests

